Decoding¶

Can we interpret the collective activities of the neurons? Suppose we want to decode the value that was encoded.

For some input value $x_p$, suppose that the neuron activities are in the vector $A_p$.

Then we want to find a set of decoding weights $D$ so that $$ A_p \cdot D = x_p $$ That is, we want a linear combintaion of the neural firing rates to give us the input.

Let's try a random set of decoding weights.

In [10]:
D = np.random.normal(size=[N])/10.
print(D)

 -0.11675393  0.12816915 -0.13132474  0.29989376]

Optimal Linear Decoding¶

We can formulate the problem as a linear least-squares problem, $$ \begin{align} A_0 \cdot D &= x_0 \\ A_1 \cdot D &= x_1 \\ & \vdots \\ A_P \cdot D &= x_P \end{align} $$ Or, in matrix form, $$ \left[ \begin{array}{c} \quad A_0^\mathrm{T} \quad \\ \hline A_1^\mathrm{T} \\ \hline \vdots \\ \hline A_P^\mathrm{T} \end{array} \right] \ D = \left[ \begin{array}{c} x_0 \\ x_1 \\ \vdots \\ x_P \end{array} \right] $$ Or, simply $$ A D = x $$ We cannot solve this in general because usually it is an over-determined system; the number of equations ($P$) is larger than the number of neurons ($N$). So, instead we seek a least-squares solution, $$ D^\ast = \mathrm{arg}\min_D \| AD - X \| $$

In [15]:
Dstar = np.linalg.lstsq(A, X, rcond=None)[0]
In [16]:
print(Dstar)

[ 0.00805434  0.01114696  0.00614956 -0.00910605  0.00696164 -0.02037743
  0.21712223  0.01465508 -0.28181323  0.00763933]
In [17]:
X_bar = A @ Dstar
plt.plot(X, X_bar, 'ro')
plt.plot(X, X, 'k--')
plt.xlabel('Input X'), plt.ylabel('Reconstruction X_bar');

Decoding Functions¶

We can decode not just $x$, but also functions of $f(x)$. $$ A D = f(x) $$

In [18]:
N = 100
pop = lif.GenerateLIFPopulation(N, [-1,1], [20,50])
P = 1000
X = np.linspace(-1, 1, P)
A = lif.Stim2Rate(X, pop)
In [19]:
F = X                # === STEP 1 ===
F = np.sin(3.14*X)   # === STEP 2 ===
F = np.abs(X)       # === STEP 2 ===
D = lif.Decoders(A, F)
